Description: Quite large fragment of a seal-impression, the fine brown Nile clay has some mica inclusions and was hardened after excavation. The rear shows one side with two coils of basketry and anotherside with one coil of basketry. Both sides show traces of secondaryfire impact. The front bears a large oval scarab-like seal-impression with a fingerprint on top distorting the motif. A circumferential line is visible around a standing bull, facing to the left, positioned in the upper part of the seal. To the left of it what looks like a seated Horus, facing to the left. A third sign was positioned under the bull, behind the falcon but is not further recognisable.
Findspot: Excavated/Findspot: Amara West (Nubia), E14.7 temple magazine
Acquisition notes: Formerly housed by the Birmingham Museum and Art Gallery and the EES London.
